Scene Processing:
This incident was recorded by my body-worn camera system. MSP Criminal Enforcement Division (CED) and MSP Crime Scene responded to the scene. Numerous photographs were taken by Crime Scene, and uploaded to VeriPic. Crime Scene lifted numerous latent fingerprints from the scene. Video footage evidence from surrounding businesses was obtained by CED.
Physical Evidence- 1.) One (1) black antenna from the trail camera was recovered and packaged by Crime Scene, awaiting further laboratory analysis.
2.) One (1) black SD card from the trail camera was recovered and packaged by CED, awaiting further analysis.
 
Narrative:
    On January 17, 2023 at approximately 1420 hours, I, Trooper Pettyjohn #7121, currently assigned to the Maryland State Police Westminster Barrack, was dispatched to Plunkert Construction located at 2601 Emory Road, Finksburg, Maryland 21048 (Building #5) for a burglary/theft that had previously occurred.

Upon my arrival, I made contact with the owner of Plunkert Construction who I identified as Plunkert, Jonothan Joseph Lee (W/M, DOB: 11/03/1978). Plunkert stated that he arrived at work when he observed that there was numerous pieces of equipment missing, a work trailer was damaged, and his trail camera was taken from the steel cage housing that is mounted to the top of the building. Plunkert stated that he made contact with the nearby businesses, which had video footage of two (2) or three (3) males gain access into the shop building as well as the enclosed trailer, remove numerous pieces of equipment and load them in the back of a pickup truck. Plunkert provided me with a rough estimate of at least $20,000.00 in construction equipment that was stolen. Plunkert stated most of the items were chainsaws, blowers, string trimmers, augers, power tools, etc.

I observed the trailer to be a gray Unlimited enclosed work trailer with apparent pry marks to the left side access door. The trailer was displaying Maine registration 2459377 (VIN: 56JTE2424HA153135).

Plunkert stated that he had a bluetooth trail camera mounted on the top front of his shop building that was in a steel cage housing with a lock on it. He advised that was stolen as well. I observed the steel cage housing to be damaged and broken, with the lock still intact and attached to it.

I then observed the rear side door of the shop building with apparent pry marks from where the suspects gained access into the shop building. Plunkert escorted me through the shop building and advised where some of the items were located before they were stolen.

I then made contact with the employees of the nearby business, Erosion Control and Geotextile Distributors located at building #8 and reviewed their video footage. At approximately 0430 hours on 01/15/2023, their video footage revealed a white pickup truck with no registration plates attached drive by the business and proceed to building #5 where three (3) male subjects exited the white pickup truck. One (1) subject proceeded to the trailer, another subject proceeded to climb a pile of wood pallets to reach the trail camera, and the other male proceeded to the doors of the shop building. The subject at the trailer proceeded to pry open the trailer door, gain access and then begin to retrieve numerous equipment items and place them in the bed of the white pickup truck. The other subject climbed a pile of wood pallets and appeared to be striking the trail camera housing with a blunt force object and then gain access taking the trail camera. The last subject proceeded to the front side door of the building and was unable to make access to the door and then proceed to the rear side door and appear to strike the door with a blunt force object and also pry at the door. Eventually all three (3) subjects gained access to the building where they eventually exited through the front side door with numerous equipment items and then placing them in the bed of the white pickup truck. This continued for approximately fifteen (15) to twenty (20) minutes when they eventually fled the scene with bed of the pickup truck visibly filled with numerous equipment items.

I then made contact with the owner of Paul’s Trucking and Equipment Repair located at building #3 and reviewed the video footage. The video footage revealed the white pickup truck with no registration plates enter the business park at approximately 0430 hours with an empty truck bed. At approximately 0450 hours, the white pickup truck flees the business park and the truck bed is visibly filled with numerous equipment items.

After reviewing the footage, the white pickup truck appeared to be an early 2000’s white Dodge Dakota.

I was then provided information to a Detective from the Baltimore County Police Department that has been investigating numerous cases from surrounding counties with similar circumstances.

I made contact with Detective J. Layhew #5501 (443-801-2879) from the Baltimore County Police Department. Layhew advised me that he has been investigating cases from surrounding counties with similar circumstances that originally started in Baltimore County, in August. He stated that there has been approximately twenty five (25) to thirty (30) different cases in the past six (6) months, in multiple counties where a vehicle enters a construction type business with a vehicle that has no registration plates attached and steals numerous equipment items. Layhew estimated the total amount of equipment stolen to be approximately $400,000.00 to $500,000.00.

At that time I requested MSP Criminal Enforcement Division (CED) and MSP Crime Scene to respond to the scene for further investigation.

Cpl. Buck #6037 from CED and MSP Crime Scene responded to the scene.

Cpl. Buck #6037 retrieved copies of all video footage evidence.

Crime Scene personnel photographed the scene, and all photographs were uploaded to VeriPic. Crime Scene then dusted the scene for fingerprints, and lifted numerous latent fingerprints from the scene. All latent prints were collected by Crime Scene personnel and transported to the MSP Crime Lab for further analysis.

While investigating the scene, Crime Lab personal recovered one (1) black antenna from the trail camera that was located on top of the enclosed trailer. The antenna was packaged and processed by Crime Scene personnel, awaiting further laboratory analysis.

Also recovered, was One (1) black SD card from the trail camera. The SD card was packaged and processed by Cpl. Buck #6037, awaiting further analysis.

Plunkert provided me with a list of all the stolen equipment, an estimate for the damaged trailer, and a copy of the Amazon listing for the trail camera stolen.

      I, Cpl. Theodore Buck of the Maryland State Police Criminal Enforcement Division completed this supplement to update the case file on the known facts of the case.  Specifically, it will outline why I believe the three subjects listed below are the suspects in this case (as of 06/07/2023).  It should be noted that I did not personally investigate all the crimes referenced below, but instead, the suspects listed below are believed to be responsible for almost a half-a-million dollars of loss to businesses across Maryland - investigated by multiple agencies.  It is believed that the case files should be obtained referenced below for exact case details to confirm the content.  This overview is meant to articulate the probable cause for issuing three search warrants for phone records (Verizon, AT&T, T-Mobile).  Based on the information below, I believe that said records will place the suspects at Plunkert Construction - at the time of the Burglary and Theft.  It should be noted that Det. J. Layhew is considered the lead investigator of the below-listed suspects.  Det Layhew provided most of the background information provided below.  Please see the attached copy of one of Det. Layhew's Court Orders for further information.

UPDATED CASE INFORMATION
 
Initial Investigations into the above SUSPECTS:

      Since the initial report, I have been in contact with Det. Layhew of the Baltimore County Police Department.  The information provided below is a summary of the Det. Layhew's investigation.  Please see the copy of the Order Det. Layhew authored, which outlines his investigative efforts.

      During the latter part of 2022, numerous burglaries and thefts started occurring in the Baltimore County area, which led Det. Layhew to become involved with the case.  It was soon learned that numerous allied agencies also had cases with similar M.O.s to the cases Baltimore County was investigating.  

      On 11/16/2022, Ofc. Kubitz #6409 (Baltimore County Police Department) took a report for Allen & Sons Tree Services located at 7801 Harford Rd (22-320-0606). Unknown suspect(s) forced open a garage door and removed a considerable amount of tools and a dirt bike. There was no surveillance video at the business. Later in the evening of the same day, a family member found a Facebook Marketplace ad for chainsaws that they could identify as being stolen from Allen & Sons Tree Services. They were listed by an “Elvis Granados”. A meet was set up to attempt to buy the chainsaws. Once they met, Ben Allen (owner) was able to verify that the chainsaws were, in fact, ones stolen from his business. 8 Police Patrol units were called, and Elvis Granados was arrested. Four chainsaws were seized, photographed, and returned to Ben Allen.

      On 11/17/2022, Detective Layhew #5501 and Detective Grauel #4185 (both with Baltimore County Police) were notified that Elvis Granados may still have chainsaws from Allen & Sons Tree Services. He had other Facebook Marketplace ads listed for items NOT recovered by Police the night prior. Detectives checked and noted that Elvis Granados was released on his own recognizance. Detectives responded to 807 Jaydee Ave, which was listed as the residence of Elvis Granados. Detectives talked to Elvis Granados with the aid of Det. Gargurevich, who was needed to help translate. The following was learned:
  • Elvis Granados purchased the chainsaws from a person he knew as “Tomi”.
  • He met “Tomi” at the Pasadena Flea Market a month or two prior.
  • He had purchased other tools and equipment from “Tomi”.
    • He had already deleted his text messages in his cell phone with “Tomi”.
  • “Tomi” would call him and offer to sell him tools.
  • “Tomi” would often have a lot of used power tools for sale.
  • Granados did not know where “Tomi” obtained the tools from.
  • “Tomi” was saved into his cell phone as “Tomi Eramienta” with phone number 443-386- 0701.
    • The phone was identified as belonging to James ERMER
  • “Tomi’s” brother was with “Tomi” often when they met.
  • “Tomi’s” brother would drive a red Honda sedan.
  • “Tomi’s” brother was saved into his cell phone as “Hermano De Tomi” with phone number 703-987-3361.
    • The phone was identified as belonging to Tyler SCHRACK 
  • “Tomi” drove a blue in color SUV, possibly a Chevy or GMC.
  • “Tomi” and his brother were white males.
  • “Tomi” had a black male friend that drove a white pickup truck.
  • He did not know the name or number of the black male.
  • Granados had more tools that he purchased from “Tomi” in his garage.
       I was further advised that while Det. Layhew was speaking with this subject (Granados); he recognized the suspects Granados described as matching the descriptions of the suspects seen in other similar cases.  Det. Layhew further advised that these incidents were not just limited to Baltimore County, adding that Anne Arundel County Police, MTA Police, and other agencies had cases involving the suspects.   

      On 11/19/22, Ben Allen (owner of Allen & Sons Tree Services) again notified police that he saw on Facebook Marketplace that some of his stolen saws were being advertised for sale. In the background of the pictures containing what he believed to be his stolen property was a blue truck with a missing rear hubcap and damage/rust holes in the rear fender. Also in the picture inside the truck were a pair of red running shoes and a white construction hat. Later that afternoon, patrol officers from PC06 (Towson) located a blue GMC Yukon (believed to be the suspect vehicle described by Ben Allen) at the Days Inn located at 8712 Loch Raven Blvd (21286) and maintained surveillance on the vehicle until detectives arrived. The GMC was backed into a parking spot where the rear tag could not be seen, and there was no front tag. Burglary Unit Detectives took over surveillance and were able to observe the rear tag bearing Maryland registration 8FC1328 VIN: 1GKFK16Z63J138239.  The vehicle also had a missing rear hubcap and damage/rust holes in a rear fender, just as in the Facebook Marketplace posting; however, when detectives looked in through the window, the stolen property was not there, only the red running shoes and white construction hat. The missing rear hubcap and damage/rust holes in a rear fender also appear to match the blue GMC Yukon seen on surveillance video at the burglary at A-AAA on 10/13/2022 and at the CMB Construction burglary in Anne Arundel County on 10/26/2022. Additionally, the pattern of the oxidized paint above the vehicle's windshield matched what had been seen on surveillance videos. A check of the MD registration 8FC1328 revealed that it was registered to a James Matthew Ermer Jr M/W 12/3/2002. Det. Grauel authored and obtained a Court Order to place a GPS device on the GMC Yukon installed on 11/19/2022.  Due to the fact that Elvis Granados also described what could be the same blue GMC Yukon, Det. Grauel authored and obtained a court order for the cell phone records for the phone that Elvis contacted, “Tomi” 443-386-0701. This cell phone number was serviced by T-Mobile. Subscriber information provided by T-Mobile revealed that it belonged to JAMES ERMER, 1004 CRAIN HWY N, GLEN BURNIE, MD 21061. This was the same address listed in MD MVA for the blue GMC Yukon with tag 8FC1328.

      It was around this time Det. Layhew started networking with allied agencies to try and build the cases.  Det. Layhew indicated that MTA Police took a report that further tied the suspects to my case and all of his.  It was learned that on 8/30/2022, MTA Police took a report for Bourn Environmental LLC (Report number 22-MTA-0002962). Bourn Environmental LLC was operating a construction site at the MTA Light Rail stop located at 202 Warren Rd in Cockeysville, MD. During the overnight of 8/29/22 to 8/30/22, unknown suspect(s) broke into a storage trailer on site and stole a considerable about of equipment and tools. One of the items was later located and posted for sale on Facebook Marketplace by Tyler T-roc Schrack. This tool was a Proton Bak welder, which is a unique and uncommon tool to find for sale. MTA detectives made several attempts to make contact with Tyler T-roc Schrack to view and match the tool as being stolen. The identity of Tyler T-roc Schrack was confirmed to be Tyler Joseph Schrack M/W 10/17/1993, by his MD MVA record and photo. These images also matched the Facebook profile for Tyler T-roc Schrack. Contact was eventually made with Tyler Schrack, who provided his contact phone number as 703-987-3361. He did initially give the phone number of 410-935-4397, but MTA Police called this number and confirmed that it belonged to Tyler Schrack’s girlfriend Talisa Anderson. MTA also confirmed with Parole and Probation that both of these numbers were provided to them by Tyler Schrack on 12/12/2022 as his contact phone numbers.


Further Investigation and Cell Phone Orders obtained by Baltimore County Police:

      As referenced above, a GMC Yukon was known to Law Enforcement as likely being a vehicle utilized by the suspects in multiple burglaries and thefts in the area.  A GPS was placed on the GMC Yukon, but as of 12/16/2022, the blue GMC Yukon 8FC1328 was still parked at the Days Inn. The GPS was removed because the vehicle had not moved since the GPS was installed. Det. Layhew met with a manager from Days Inn (name and number are in the current case file retained by Det. Layhew). She reviewed the surveillance video and found that the blue GMC Yukon was last moved on 11/16/2022. A white male wearing glasses exited the truck and walked in and out of room 142.  A check of room 142 (in the hotel's system) showed that it was rented to Tyler Schrack (MD MVA S-620-809-441-800) between 11/10/2022 and 11/20/2022. This was the same Tyler Schrack that MTA Police had previous contact with for their case. He provided the telephone number 443-486-0701; no vehicle was listed on the agreement. It was noted that this telephone number was one digit off from the number belonging to James Ermer Jr (actual number 443-386-0701).  A check of the other rented rooms revealed that the blue GMC Yukon was not listed. A further check showed that no rooms were currently listed for Tyler Schrack or James Ermer.  Detective Layhew has viewed images of Tyler Schrack and James Ermer, and Facebook profiles for both. Det. Layhew was able to confirm that the white male wearing glasses on the surveillance video from Days Inn was in fact Tyler Schrack.

      Det. Layhew obtained data provided by T-Mobile, which showed phone number 443-386-0701 spent a considerable amount of time in the area of the Days Inn on Loch Raven Blvd. The same location of the blue GMC Yukon 8FC1328 and where Tyler Schrack was renting a room from 11/5/2022 to 11/20/2022.  Det. Layhew advised he has reviewed surveillance video, pictures, and observed the blue GMC Yukon 8FC1328 in person and believes it to be the same blue GMC Yukon used by the suspects in multiple cases. Due to the fact that it is still parked at Days Inn leads Det. Layhew to believe that this vehicle is disabled or no longer in play by the suspects.  

      On 12/22/2022, Det. Layhew obtained Court Orders for these three cell phone numbers and served them on their respective Carriers. Data obtained from these records places 443-386-0701 (James Ermer) and 703-987-3361 (Tyler Schrack) devices at the following cases:

2023 Case Events - Events locating the white suspect truck and events placing the suspects at THIS crime.

      It should be noted that this section mentions when incidents were reported, so the dates should be considered approximate.  For instance, the burglary at Plunkert Construction actually occurred back on January 15, 2023 - according to surveillance video.  

      On 1/17/2023, Maryland State Police MSP took a report for Plunkert Construction located at 162601 Emory Rd, Finksburg, MD 21048 (23-MSP-002013). See previous supplements for further information.  At least two suspects were visible, and they were operating a white Dodge Dakota single-cab truck.  Total loss was over approximately $40,000.00 - see the estimated value of items lost provided by the victim in this case. 

      On 1/17/2023, Ofc. Ponce Vargas #5647 took a report for Pittman Tree & Landscaping, who had service vehicles parked at 306 Mt Carmel Rd that were broken into. This location is a lot/facility that belongs to MD State Highway Administration. Suspects stole power tools from the targeted vehicles. Surveillance video found nearby revealed that the suspects parked at Graul’s Market. Two suspects were visible and were operating an early 2000s model Dodge Dakota single-cab truck. No license plate was visible on the truck.  The total loss is estimated to be $2,550.00.  

      On 1/18/2023, Ofc. Davidson #6617 took a report for Allan Myers who has a current construction site at The Bradshaw Road overpass for I95 (23-018-0632). During the overnight hours of 1/17/23 into 1/18/2023,  unknown suspect(s) entered the construction site and cut the locks off of several conex/sea containers being used to store equipment, tools, and material.  The locks were not found. Several pieces of tools and equipment were stolen from the conex/sea containers and gasoline was siphoned from two utility trucks parked at the site. There was no surveillance video at the site.  The total loss is estimated to be $5,350.00.  Det. Layhew showed the toll images with equipment in the bed of the white Dodge Dakota to the Complainant from Allan Myers, who replied, “yes some of those items I can say are what was stolen from me”.
      
      On 1/18/2023, MSP Trooper Payne handled a 2nd Degree Burglary at the construction site located at the Mountain Rd overpass over I95. Unknown suspects forced entry into storage containers on site and stole tools and equipment. It was also noted that approximately 50 gallons of fuel were siphoned from vehicles parked on site. An employee arriving at the site observed a white pickup truck leaving the area at a high rate of speed.  

      Det. Layhew was able to view still images from the surveillance video from Plunkert and Pittman. The white Dodge Dakota pickup truck was noted to be the same body style. Further noted that there were stickers in the back window that matched, aftermarket chrome exhaust tip, and same style wheels. Det. Layhew checked updated cell phone records for “443-386-0701: James Ermer” from T-Mobile. Records place this cell phone at all four of these new cases as well.

      Based on this information, Det. Layhew and I believe that the same Dodge Dakota truck was used in these recent cases. On 1/18/2023, Det. Layhew and other Detectives from the Burglary unit responded to the area of the phone pings for “443-386-0701: James Ermer” from T-Mobile. Located in the driveway of 2217 Silver Lane Road, Essex, MD was a single-cab white Dodge Dakota with MD license plate 1Z6599. It also had the same stickers in the back window, aftermarket chrome exhaust tip, and the same style wheels. Further noted from the video from Graul’s Market, the truck's “5.9 R/T” model decals and fender flares were visible on the Dakota parked in the driveway. Based on that observation and the cell phone pings, Det. Layhew believes this Dakota to be the suspect vehicle used in the burglaries at Plunkert Construction and Pittman Tree & Landscaping.  An MVA check of 1Z6599 revealed that it was registered to a Coleen Schoolden with a listed address of 2217 Silver Lane Rd. A check through Calls for Service and Traffic Stops revealed that the last person stopped in the white Dodge Dakota 1Z6599 was Nicholas Morrow, M/W 3/18/2004 MD MVA# M600630465204. Det. Layhew authored and obtained a Court Order to utilize a GPS device on the white Dodge Dakota 1Z6599. This was installed on 1/19/23.
    
      Det. Layhew obtained a subpoena and subsequently served it on MDTA/EZPass for MD license plate 1Z6599. Images provided showed this plate on the white Dodge Dakota identified in the burglaries. This vehicle traveled through the Francis Scott Key Bridge toll before and after the burglary at Plunkert Construction on 1/15/23. In addition, toll images dated 1/18/23 showed the bed of the white Dodge Dakota loaded with what appeared to be power tools and equipment. In these toll images, the driver was identified to be Nicholas Morrow.
       
      

Operation Confirming these Subjects as the SUSPECTS:

      On 1/22/2023, Detective Layhew organized members of Baltimore County Police and Maryland State Police to conduct physical and electronic surveillance on the white Dodge Dakota with Maryland registration: 1Z6599.  I assisted with this operation.

      This truck was parked on the street near 2945 Cornwall Rd (21222). Detectives observed three white males exit 2945 Cornwall Rd and get into the white Dodge Dakota 1Z6599. The males were observed to be substantially similar to James Ermer, Tyler Schrack, and Nick Morrow. It was also noted that no tools or equipment were visible in the bed of the truck. Detectives surveilled the truck and males down to PG County. The white truck and males entered a residential construction site located at Enterprise Rd and Traditions Blvd. A short time later, the white pickup truck was observed exiting the construction site with equipment and tools visible in the bed of the truck. Detectives entered the construction site and were able to confirm that a burglary had occurred and that the suspects (3 males) had forced entry into at least one locked conex/sea container that the business used for storage.

      The white Dodge Dakota was surveilled to Limit Ave and Falkirk Rd in Baltimore, 21239. There the males were observed throwing tools and equipment out of the truck and quickly sped off in the truck. Det. Layhew stayed with the tools and equipment to recover them. During this recovery, Aviation directed Det. Layhew to the rear drive of 6401 Falkirk Rd 21239, advising that one of the suspects had hidden something there. Sticking out of a green trash can were the handles of a set of bolt cutters.  With the aid of Aviation, other detectives followed the white Dodge Dakota 1Z6599 and the suspects to a nearby gas station, where two of the three suspects were apprehended. The two were identified as Nicholas Morrow and James Ermer Jr. While waiting for transport Nicholas Morrow stated that the third suspect had jumped out of the truck while it was moving.

      During a search incident to arrest, an iPhone in a white and gray case was seized. This was believed to be the Apple iPhone XR with IMEI: 353053109044513 and telephone number 443-386-0701 being owned and operated by James Matthew Ermer Jr.

Tools and Equipment recovered included:
  • Two generators
  • A white bucket with nails, screws, and a tool belt
  • A Stihl chop saw
  • Two large Dewalt tool bags containing numerous Dewalt power tools
  • An empty blue toolbox
  • A pair of red and black bolt cutters
      Det. Layhew observed “Kinsley” written in black marker on several tools and knew that Kinsley Construction was a large construction company that operated in the area/region. Due to the time of this incident, no contact with Kinsley could be made.  The report for this incident was handled by PG County under report number PP23012200000320.


Locating the Third Suspect - Tyler Schrack:

      After the operation referenced above, Det. Layhew advised that he believed the third suspect was Tyler Schrack.  Detectives set up to watch 2945 Cornwall Rd to see if he returned. Noted during this surveillance operation was that the cell phone number belonging to Tyler Schrack, 703-987-3361 was pinging in the area around 2945 Cornwall Rd while the suspects committed the burglary.

      On 1/22/2023, a Search and Seizure Warrant was obtained and executed at 2945 Cornwall Rd, 2nd Floor Apartment, 21222. The only occupants of the apartment were Talisa Anderson and Tyler Schrack. Tyler Schrack was arrested for his outstanding VOP warrant and transported to Precinct 9. Talisa Delia Anderson B/F 3/19/2004, identified by her MD MVA driving record and photo, was the known girlfriend of Tyler Schrack.  During a search of the property, numerous cellular phones were located, along with multiple firearms (some of which were "ghost" guns, meaning no identifiers).  Tyler Schrack and James Ermer Jr were both prohibited from possessing a firearm.  

 

Post Miranda Interviews of the Suspects - provided by Det. Layhew:

MORROW

      In a post-Miranda interview with Nicholas Morrow, he denied ever being inside the residence belonging to Tyler Schrack or James Ermer Jr. Further, he stated that Tyler Schrack and James Ermer Jr did not use their real names when they went out together; James went by “Tommy” and Tyler went by “John.” These were common names used to conceal their true identity. This also corroborates the statement provided by Elvis Granados that he knew them as “Tomi” and “Tomi’s brother.” He also provided his cell phone number, 410-805-5276.

      Specifically related to this case, Det. Layhew advised me that Morrow indirectly referenced the incident at Plunkert Construction.  Det. Layhew stated that Morrow said he "drove" Schrack and Ermer "a long way" but would not specifically state the location.  Morrow also reportedly advised Det. Layhew that afterward; they went to the flea market (Anne Arundel County).  Det. Layhew believes that cell record data will put them in Finksburg during the time of the incident, as well as the location of the flea market in Anne Arundel County (later that day).  


SCHRACK

      Refused to speak with investigators.


ERMER

      Spoke to Det. Layhew, and advised him that they had been "hitting" places numerous times over the last couple of months - but would not provide exact locations.  Ermer reportedly told Det. Layhew that he was "doing this" to pay bills.  Det. Layhew advised that Ermer said he was the one who drove them places.  Ermer tied himself to the blue Yukon mentioned above, stating that the transmission blew.  

 

Search Warrants for Phone Numbers of the Suspects:

      Based on the information above, I authored three search warrants for this case.  These search warrants are for Verizon, T-Mobile, and AT&T, all of which are related to the suspects listed above.  On May 21, 2023, I sent the search warrants to the Honorable Judge F. Hecker of the Circuit Court of Maryland in Carroll County.  On May 26, 2023, I received the signed search warrants from the Honorable Judge F. Hecker.  Copies of the warrants have been included with the case file for review.  

      On May 26, 2023, at approximately 05:15 P.M., I emailed AT&T (gldc@att.com) a copy of the signed AT&T search warrant.  On May 26, 2023, at approximately 05:17, I emailed T-Mobile (lerinbound@t-mobile.com) a copy of the signed T-Mobile search warrant.  On May 26, 2023, at 05:21 P.M., I emailed Verizon (VSAT.CCT@one.verizon.com) a copy of the signed Verizon search warrant.  Once records are received, the information will be included in the case file for review. 



Case OPEN.

Narrative:

      On approximately May 29, 2023, I, Cpl. Theodore Buck of the Maryland State Police Criminal Enforcement Division received the records from T-Mobile.  Due to various cases, I was not able to access/view the records until June 8, 2023.  In a review of the records, I observed that the phone number listed on the warrant is actually an AT&T number - and a search warrant had already been sent to AT&T for that number.  Thus, the records from T-Mobile advised that they did not have any files related to the 703-987-3361.  Another search warrant is required for T-Mobile, which will be for phone number: 443-386-0701.

      On June 8, 2023, at approximately 01:05 P.M., I sent a search warrant return to the Honorable Judge F. Hecker of the Circuit Court of Maryland in Carroll County.  Prior to sending the return, I advised the Judge's office of the update and that a second search warrant was pending for T-Mobile.

      On June 8, 2023, at approximately 01:45 P.M., I sent an updated T-Mobile search warrant to the Honorable Judge F. Hecker.  This search warrant is for 443-386-0701.  

      On June 8, 2023, at approximately 03:30 P.M., I received the search warrant return for the first T-Mobile search warrant.  Shortly after, I also received the signed search warrant for the second T-Mobile search warrant.  Copies of both items have been included with the case file for review.

      On June 8, 2023, at approximately 04:15 P.M., I sent a copy of the signed search warrant to T-Mobile.  



Case to remain OPEN.

Narrative:

      On November 29, 2023, I, Cpl. Theodore Buck of the Maryland State Police Criminal Enforcement Division conducted a recorded interview with Nicholas MORROW, one of the suspects in this case.  The interview was conducted at the law office of Attorney J. Turnbull in Towson, Maryland.  The interview was recorded using my agency-issued body-worn camera.  Before conducting the interview, Attorney J. Turnbull advised MORROW about the interview and his rights.

      The following is a summary of the recorded interview.  Please review the footage for exact comments and statements made.  

      During the interview, MORROW would confess to being involved in numerous tool thefts in the area, including the one from this case.  Importantly, MORROW would identify the other suspects in this case as the same ones he was caught with during the operation led by Baltimore County Police - Det. Layhew.  The other suspects have been identified as Tyler SCHRACK and James ERMER.  According to MORROW, the other suspects would direct him on where to drive and indicated he did not know where he was going in this case.  MORROW did admit that his role was to provide the truck for the other suspects to load the stolen tools into.  MORROW did not initially recognize the location in this case, but after discussing the incident, he started picking out things specific to the location.  At one point, he mentioned the train tracks near the victim's business and also driving to a lower lot and having to turn around (confirmed by the surveillance video).  It should be noted that I was assisted by using Google Maps to show the area.    

      MORROW would go on to advise that for this incident, he only drove his vehicle (with SCHRACK and ERMER) to the victim's business.  MORROW stated that he did not get out of the vehicle, adding that he fell asleep.  MORROW advised that it was the other two suspects who loaded the vehicle with the tools, which "weighed" it down.  MORROW was not able to advise how SCHRACK and ERMER were able to get into the business to steal the tools.  After waking, MORROW recalled the bed of the truck having tools in it.  MORROW identified some of the tools he observed in the truck as weed hackers, backpack blowers, hedge trimmers, and chainsaws.  In another part of the interview, MORROW indicated that he got out of the vehicle to use the restroom; however, MORROW did not advise he went into the business.  Following the crime, MORROW advised that he drove them back to their residence.  When asked what happened with the tools, MORROW stated he could not remember if he drove them to the flea market but added that there was a "good possibility" he drove them there.  MORROW was asked about what he got in return for allowing the use of the truck.  MORROW advised that he would generally receive a "couple hundred bucks" (cash), later estimating approximately $400.  

      During the interview, MORROW provided examples of tracking countermeasures used by the suspects.  MORROW advised that they, reportedly SCHRACK or ERMER, would remove the license plate from the truck.  MORROW also advised that he "probably" turned off his phone before the crime.

      Following the interview, I advised MORROW and his attorney that I would be contacting the Carroll County State's Attorney's Office to advise them of this interview.

Narrative:

      Following the interview of the suspect (MORROW), who confessed to this crime and identified two other suspects, I reviewed the case with Assistant State's Attorney (ASA) E. Ingraham.  I was asked to contact the victim to check if he recognized any suspect names and get any insurance documents he received when he filed this with his insurance company.  I was advised that this case would likely go before a Grand Jury around January 2024.  

      On December 18, 2023, I spoke with the victim in this case, Plunkert.  I updated him on the case status, and he indicated that he was willing to be involved in the proceedings.  Plunkert advised that he would send me the insurance information/documents, advising that he did receive a payment for the losses.  Additionally, I reviewed the suspects' names with Plunkert, who advised that he did not know the suspects.  According to Plunkert, they should not have felt they were allowed to enter his business and take his property.  The suspects had no rights or ownership of the items.  It should be noted that Plunkert was contacted by the Baltimore County Police Department about the same suspects, adding that he told them that he did not recognize them.  Plunkert indicated he knew some details of that case, but I did not ask anything specific and determined I should notify ASA Ingraham. 

      In a follow-up conversation with ASA Ingraham, I was advised that this case is pending further review for a possible January Grand Jury.
